So kinda but not really.

Yes, 35mm film through a good high-end 35mm projector will have the source analog quality that TECHNICALLY can't be fully reproduced from a digital scan, however, modern displays and projectors are MUCH higher spec and the original 35mm film master was color graded and mastered for SDR color space and ~10-20k lumens at most.

However, a modern cinema projector (Xenon laser) can do true digital 4k 4:4:4 120fps with HDR (wide color gamut coverage) and can easily go beyond 50,000 lumens. Which would look better (cleaner picture quality, much deeper blacks, punchier highlights, and a wider color space) than the original 35mm source projected through a 35mm film projector.

I'd ALSO argue you get many benefits even from a simple home theatre setup using a modern OLED in a dark room. Since you have infinite black levels, per-pixel brightness control, and potentially 700-1000+ nits of HDR highlights. This wouldn't rival the sheer sense of scale you get from seeing the 35mm source film on a real cinema screen, but for a home viewing experience it's fantastic and the contrast and black levels especially will make it better than the 35mm in at least that respect.
tldr; yes 35mm film can still look amazing, but there are some big improvements in recent years that would allow the UHD bluray to be visually superior with the proper theater setup.
